        "paragraph_index": 0,
        "text": "## Oxalic Acid pKa Values\n\n**Oxalic acid** (ethanedioic acid, SMILES: `O=C(O)C(=O)O`) is a **diprotic acid** (H₂L) with **two dissociation steps**:\n\n| Step | Reaction | pKa | T (°C) | I (M) |\n|------|----------|-----|--------|-------|\n| pKa₁ | H₂L ⇌ HL⁻ + H⁺ | **3.8** | 25 | 0.1 |\n| pKa₂ | HL⁻ ⇌ L²⁻ + H⁺ | **−1.2** | 25 | 0.1 |\n\n> ⚠️ **Note on ordering:** In SRD-46, pKa values are stored in the *protonation* direction (log β for H⁺ + L ⇌ HL). The value **3.8** corresponds to the **first deprotonation** (H₂L → HL⁻), and **−1.2** corresponds to the **second deprotonation** (HL⁻ → L²⁻). The negative pKa₂ reflects that the half-protonated form HL⁻ is a *very strong acid* — essentially fully dissociated under normal conditions.",
