      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Key Chemistry Insights\n\n- **Two dissociation steps** are confirmed, consistent with oxalic acid's dicarboxylic structure (two –COOH groups).\n- The large gap between pKa₁ (3.8) and pKa₂ (−1.2) is unusual: the first –COOH is a moderately weak acid, while the second is extraordinarily strong due to the strong electron-withdrawing effect of the adjacent carboxylate group.\n- At physiological or near-neutral pH, oxalic acid exists almost entirely as the fully deprotonated **oxalate dianion (L²⁻)**, which is why it readily precipitates calcium as insoluble calcium oxalate (kidney stones!).\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46 (ligand_8872, vlm_151494 & vlm_151532), measured at 25°C, I = 0.1 M.*",
